38 def _aligned_zeros(shape, dtype=float, order="C", align=None):
39 """
40 Allocate a new ndarray with aligned memory.
41  
42 The ndarray is guaranteed *not* aligned to twice the requested alignment.
43 Eg, if align=4, guarantees it is not aligned to 8. If align=None uses
44 dtype.alignment."""
45 dtype = np.dtype(dtype)
46 if dtype == np.dtype(object):
47 # Can't do this, fall back to standard allocation (which
48 # should always be sufficiently aligned)
49 if align is not None:
50 raise ValueError("object array alignment not supported")
51 return np.zeros(shape, dtype=dtype, order=order)
52 if align is None:
53 align = dtype.alignment
54 if not hasattr(shape, '__len__'):
55 shape = (shape,)
56 size = functools.reduce(operator.mul, shape) * dtype.itemsize
57 buf = np.empty(size + 2*align + 1, np.uint8)
58  
59 ptr = buf.__array_interface__['data'][0]
60 offset = ptr % align
61 if offset != 0:
62 offset = align - offset
63 if (ptr % (2*align)) == 0:
64 offset += align
65  
66 # Note: slices producing 0-size arrays do not necessarily change
67 # data pointer --- so we use and allocate size+1
68 buf = buf[offset:offset+size+1][:-1]
69 data = np.ndarray(shape, dtype, buf, order=order)
70 data.fill(0)
71 return data

161 # Test that the writeable flag can be changed for an array wrapping

177 arr_writeable.flags.writeable = False
178

180 assert not arr_readonly.flags.owndata
181 assert not arr_readonly.flags.writeable

187 assert not arr.flags.writeable
188  
189 with assert_raises(ValueError):
190 view.flags.writeable = True

193 warnings.simplefilter("error", DeprecationWarning)
194 with assert_raises(DeprecationWarning):
195 arr.flags.writeable = True

258 class TestHash:
259 # see #3793
260 def test_int(self):
261 for st, ut, s in [(np.int8, np.uint8, 8),
262 (np.int16, np.uint16, 16),
263 (np.int32, np.uint32, 32),
264 (np.int64, np.uint64, 64)]:
265 for i in range(1, s):
266 assert_equal(hash(st(-2**i)), hash(-2**i),
267 err_msg="%r: -2**%d" % (st, i))
268 assert_equal(hash(st(2**(i - 1))), hash(2**(i - 1)),
269 err_msg="%r: 2**%d" % (st, i - 1))
270 assert_equal(hash(st(2**i - 1)), hash(2**i - 1),
271 err_msg="%r: 2**%d - 1" % (st, i))
272  
273 i = max(i - 1, 1)
274 assert_equal(hash(ut(2**(i - 1))), hash(2**(i - 1)),
275 err_msg="%r: 2**%d" % (ut, i - 1))
276 assert_equal(hash(ut(2**i - 1)), hash(2**i - 1),
277 err_msg="%r: 2**%d - 1" % (ut, i))

344 def make_array(size, offset, strides):
345 try:
346 r = np.ndarray([size], dtype=int, buffer=x,
347 offset=offset*x.itemsize)
348 except Exception as e:
349 raise RuntimeError(e)
350 r.strides = strides = strides*x.itemsize
351 return r
352

355 assert_raises(ValueError, make_array, 4, 4, -2)
356 assert_raises(ValueError, make_array, 4, 2, -1)

514 class TestAssignment:
515 def test_assignment_broadcasting(self):
516 a = np.arange(6).reshape(2, 3)
517  
518 # Broadcasting the input to the output
519 a[...] = np.arange(3)
520 assert_equal(a, [[0, 1, 2], [0, 1, 2]])
521 a[...] = np.arange(2).reshape(2, 1)
522 assert_equal(a, [[0, 0, 0], [1, 1, 1]])
523  
524 # For compatibility with <= 1.5, a limited version of broadcasting
525 # the output to the input.
526 #
527 # This behavior is inconsistent with NumPy broadcasting
528 # in general, because it only uses one of the two broadcasting
529 # rules (adding a new "1" dimension to the left of the shape),
530 # applied to the output instead of an input. In NumPy 2.0, this kind
531 # of broadcasting assignment will likely be disallowed.
532 a[...] = np.arange(6)[::-1].reshape(1, 2, 3)
533 assert_equal(a, [[5, 4, 3], [2, 1, 0]])
534 # The other type of broadcasting would require a reduction operation.
535  
536 def assign(a, b):
537 a[...] = b
538  
539 assert_raises(ValueError, assign, a, np.arange(12).reshape(2, 2, 3))

804 def test_overlapping_assignment(self):
805 # With positive strides
806 a = np.arange(4)
807 a[:-1] = a[1:]
808 assert_equal(a, [1, 2, 3, 3])
809  
810 a = np.arange(4)
811 a[1:] = a[:-1]
812 assert_equal(a, [0, 0, 1, 2])
813  
814 # With positive and negative strides
815 a = np.arange(4)
816 a[:] = a[::-1]
817 assert_equal(a, [3, 2, 1, 0])
818  
819 a = np.arange(6).reshape(2, 3)
  • E231 Missing whitespace after ','
820 a[::-1,:] = a[:, ::-1]
821 assert_equal(a, [[5, 4, 3], [2, 1, 0]])
822  
823 a = np.arange(6).reshape(2, 3)
824 a[::-1, ::-1] = a[:, ::-1]
825 assert_equal(a, [[3, 4, 5], [0, 1, 2]])
826  
827 # With just one element overlapping
828 a = np.arange(5)
829 a[:3] = a[2:]
830 assert_equal(a, [2, 3, 4, 3, 4])
831  
832 a = np.arange(5)
833 a[2:] = a[:3]
834 assert_equal(a, [0, 1, 0, 1, 2])
835  
836 a = np.arange(5)
837 a[2::-1] = a[2:]
838 assert_equal(a, [4, 3, 2, 3, 4])
839  
840 a = np.arange(5)
841 a[2:] = a[2::-1]
842 assert_equal(a, [0, 1, 2, 1, 0])
843  
844 a = np.arange(5)
845 a[2::-1] = a[:1:-1]
846 assert_equal(a, [2, 3, 4, 3, 4])
847  
848 a = np.arange(5)
849 a[:1:-1] = a[2::-1]
850 assert_equal(a, [0, 1, 0, 1, 2])

883 with pytest.raises(TypeError):
884 np.array([b"12345", b"1234"], dtype="V")

889 with pytest.raises(TypeError):
890 np.array([b"1234", b"12345"], dtype="O").astype("V")

906 def test_too_big_error(self):
907 # 45341 is the smallest integer greater than sqrt(2**31 - 1).
908 # 3037000500 is the smallest integer greater than sqrt(2**63 - 1).
909 # We want to make sure that the square byte array with those dimensions
910 # is too big on 32 or 64 bit systems respectively.
911 if np.iinfo('intp').max == 2**31 - 1:
912 shape = (46341, 46341)
913 elif np.iinfo('intp').max == 2**63 - 1:
914 shape = (3037000500, 3037000500)
915 else:
916 return
917 assert_raises(ValueError, np.empty, shape, dtype=np.int8)
918 assert_raises(ValueError, np.zeros, shape, dtype=np.int8)
919 assert_raises(ValueError, np.ones, shape, dtype=np.int8)

1021 def test_non_sequence_sequence(self):
1022 """Should not segfault.
1023  
1024 Class Fail breaks the sequence protocol for new style classes, i.e.,
1025 those derived from object. Class Map is a mapping type indicated by
1026 raising a ValueError. At some point we may raise a warning instead
1027 of an error in the Fail case.
1028  
1029 """
1030 class Fail:
1031 def __len__(self):
1032 return 1
1033  
1034 def __getitem__(self, index):
1035 raise ValueError()
1036  
1037 class Map:
1038 def __len__(self):
1039 return 1
1040  
1041 def __getitem__(self, index):
1042 raise KeyError()
1043  
1044 a = np.array([Map()])
1045 assert_(a.shape == (1,))
1046 assert_(a.dtype == np.dtype(object))
1047 assert_raises(ValueError, np.array, [Fail()])

1258 def test_casting(self):
1259 # Check that casting a structured array to change its byte order
1260 # works
1261 a = np.array([(1,)], dtype=[('a', '<i4')])
1262 assert_(np.can_cast(a.dtype, [('a', '>i4')], casting='unsafe'))
1263 b = a.astype([('a', '>i4')])
1264 assert_equal(b, a.byteswap().newbyteorder())
1265 assert_equal(a['a'][0], b['a'][0])
1266  
1267 # Check that equality comparison works on structured arrays if
1268 # they are 'equiv'-castable
1269 a = np.array([(5, 42), (10, 1)], dtype=[('a', '>i4'), ('b', '<f8')])
1270 b = np.array([(5, 42), (10, 1)], dtype=[('a', '<i4'), ('b', '>f8')])
1271 assert_(np.can_cast(a.dtype, b.dtype, casting='equiv'))
1272 assert_equal(a == b, [True, True])
1273  
1274 # Check that 'equiv' casting can change byte order
1275 assert_(np.can_cast(a.dtype, b.dtype, casting='equiv'))
1276 c = a.astype(b.dtype, casting='equiv')
1277 assert_equal(a == c, [True, True])
1278  
1279 # Check that 'safe' casting can change byte order and up-cast
1280 # fields
1281 t = [('a', '<i8'), ('b', '>f8')]
1282 assert_(np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting='safe'))
1283 c = a.astype(t, casting='safe')
1284 assert_equal((c == np.array([(5, 42), (10, 1)], dtype=t)),
1285 [True, True])
1286  
1287 # Check that 'same_kind' casting can change byte order and
1288 # change field widths within a "kind"
1289 t = [('a', '<i4'), ('b', '>f4')]
1290 assert_(np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting='same_kind'))
1291 c = a.astype(t, casting='same_kind')
1292 assert_equal((c == np.array([(5, 42), (10, 1)], dtype=t)),
1293 [True, True])
1294  
1295 # Check that casting fails if the casting rule should fail on
1296 # any of the fields
1297 t = [('a', '>i8'), ('b', '<f4')]
1298 assert_(not np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting='safe'))
1299 assert_raises(TypeError, a.astype, t, casting='safe')
1300 t = [('a', '>i2'), ('b', '<f8')]
1301 assert_(not np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting='equiv'))
1302 assert_raises(TypeError, a.astype, t, casting='equiv')
1303 t = [('a', '>i8'), ('b', '<i2')]
1304 assert_(not np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting='same_kind'))
1305 assert_raises(TypeError, a.astype, t, casting='same_kind')
1306 assert_(not np.can_cast(a.dtype, b.dtype, casting='no'))
1307 assert_raises(TypeError, a.astype, b.dtype, casting='no')
1308  
1309 # Check that non-'unsafe' casting can't change the set of field names
1310 for casting in ['no', 'safe', 'equiv', 'same_kind']:
1311 t = [('a', '>i4')]
1312 assert_(not np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting=casting))
1313 t = [('a', '>i4'), ('b', '<f8'), ('c', 'i4')]
1314 assert_(not np.can_cast(a.dtype, t, casting=casting))

1540 def _test_cast_from_flexible(self, dtype):
1541 # empty string -> false
1542 for n in range(3):
1543 v = np.array(b'', (dtype, n))
1544 assert_equal(bool(v), False)
1545 assert_equal(bool(v[()]), False)
1546 assert_equal(v.astype(bool), False)
1547 assert_(isinstance(v.astype(bool), np.ndarray))
1548 assert_(v[()].astype(bool) is np.False_)
1549  
1550 # anything else -> true
1551 for n in range(1, 4):
1552 for val in [b'a', b'0', b' ']:
1553 v = np.array(val, (dtype, n))
1554 assert_equal(bool(v), True)
1555 assert_equal(bool(v[()]), True)
1556 assert_equal(v.astype(bool), True)
1557 assert_(isinstance(v.astype(bool), np.ndarray))
1558 assert_(v[()].astype(bool) is np.True_)

1637 zs = self._zeros(10, dt)
1638 p = pickle.dumps(zs, protocol=proto)
1639 zs2 = pickle.loads(p)
1640  
1641 assert_equal(zs.dtype, zs2.dtype)

1643 @pytest.mark.skipif(pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL < 5,
1644 reason="requires pickle protocol 5")
1645 def test_pickle_with_buffercallback(self):
1646 array = np.arange(10)
1647 buffers = []
1648 bytes_string = pickle.dumps(array, buffer_callback=buffers.append,
1649 protocol=5)
1650 array_from_buffer = pickle.loads(bytes_string, buffers=buffers)
1651 # when using pickle protocol 5 with buffer callbacks,
1652 # array_from_buffer is reconstructed from a buffer holding a view
1653 # to the initial array's data, so modifying an element in array
1654 # should modify it in array_from_buffer too.
1655 array[0] = -1
1656 assert array_from_buffer[0] == -1, array_from_buffer[0]

1848 def test_sort(self):
1849 # test ordering for floats and complex containing nans. It is only
1850 # necessary to check the less-than comparison, so sorts that
1851 # only follow the insertion sort path are sufficient. We only
1852 # test doubles and complex doubles as the logic is the same.
1853  
1854 # check doubles
1855 msg = "Test real sort order with nans"
1856 a = np.array([np.nan, 1, 0])
1857 b = np.sort(a)
1858 assert_equal(b, a[::-1], msg)
1859 # check complex
1860 msg = "Test complex sort order with nans"
1861 a = np.zeros(9, dtype=np.complex128)
1862 a.real += [np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 0]
1863 a.imag += [np.nan, 1, 0, np.nan, np.nan, 1, 0, 1, 0]
1864 b = np.sort(a)
1865 assert_equal(b, a[::-1], msg)
1866

1871 # sort for small arrays.

1903 @pytest.mark.parametrize('dtype', [np.float32, np.float64, np.longdouble])
1904 @pytest.mark.parametrize('part', ['real', 'imag'])
1905 def test_sort_complex(self, part, dtype):
1906 # test complex sorts. These use the same code as the scalars
1907 # but the compare function differs.
1908 cdtype = {
1909 np.single: np.csingle,
1910 np.double: np.cdouble,
1911 np.longdouble: np.clongdouble,
1912 }[dtype]
1913 a = np.arange(-50, 51, dtype=dtype)
1914 b = a[::-1].copy()
1915 ai = (a * (1+1j)).astype(cdtype)
1916 bi = (b * (1+1j)).astype(cdtype)
1917 setattr(ai, part, 1)
1918 setattr(bi, part, 1)
1919 for kind in self.sort_kinds:
1920 msg = "complex sort, %s part == 1, kind=%s" % (part, kind)
1921 c = ai.copy()
1922 c.sort(kind=kind)
1923 assert_equal(c, ai, msg)
1924 c = bi.copy()
1925 c.sort(kind=kind)
1926 assert_equal(c, ai, msg)

2062 def test_sort_degraded(self):
2063 # test degraded dataset would take minutes to run with normal qsort
2064 d = np.arange(1000000)
2065 do = d.copy()
2066 x = d
2067 # create a median of 3 killer where each median is the sorted second
2068 # last element of the quicksort partition
2069 while x.size > 3:
2070 mid = x.size // 2
2071 x[mid], x[-2] = x[-2], x[mid]
2072 x = x[:-2]
2073  
2074 assert_equal(np.sort(d), do)
2075 assert_equal(d[np.argsort(d)], do)

2139 def test_argsort(self):
2140 # all c scalar argsorts use the same code with different types
2141 # so it suffices to run a quick check with one type. The number
2142 # of sorted items must be greater than ~50 to check the actual
2143 # algorithm because quick and merge sort fall over to insertion
2144 # sort for small arrays.
2145  
2146 for dtype in [np.int32, np.uint32, np.float32]:
2147 a = np.arange(101, dtype=dtype)
2148 b = a[::-1].copy()
2149 for kind in self.sort_kinds:
2150 msg = "scalar argsort, kind=%s, dtype=%s" % (kind, dtype)
2151 assert_equal(a.copy().argsort(kind=kind), a, msg)
2152 assert_equal(b.copy().argsort(kind=kind), b, msg)
2153  
2154 # test complex argsorts. These use the same code as the scalars
2155 # but the compare function differs.
2156 ai = a*1j + 1
2157 bi = b*1j + 1
2158 for kind in self.sort_kinds:
2159 msg = "complex argsort, kind=%s" % kind
2160 assert_equal(ai.copy().argsort(kind=kind), a, msg)
2161 assert_equal(bi.copy().argsort(kind=kind), b, msg)
2162 ai = a + 1j
2163 bi = b + 1j
2164 for kind in self.sort_kinds:
2165 msg = "complex argsort, kind=%s" % kind

2167 assert_equal(bi.copy().argsort(kind=kind), b, msg)

2282 def test_searchsorted(self):
2283 # test for floats and complex containing nans. The logic is the
2284 # same for all float types so only test double types for now.
2285 # The search sorted routines use the compare functions for the
2286 # array type, so this checks if that is consistent with the sort
2287 # order.
2288  
2289 # check double
2290 a = np.array([0, 1, np.nan])
2291 msg = "Test real searchsorted with nans, side='l'"
2292 b = a.searchsorted(a, side='left')
2293 assert_equal(b, np.arange(3), msg)
2294 msg = "Test real searchsorted with nans, side='r'"
2295 b = a.searchsorted(a, side='right')
2296 assert_equal(b, np.arange(1, 4), msg)
2297 # check keyword arguments
2298 a.searchsorted(v=1)
2299 # check double complex
2300 a = np.zeros(9, dtype=np.complex128)
2301 a.real += [0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan]
2302 a.imag += [0, 1, 0, 1, np.nan, np.nan, 0, 1, np.nan]
2303 msg = "Test complex searchsorted with nans, side='l'"
2304 b = a.searchsorted(a, side='left')
2305 assert_equal(b, np.arange(9), msg)
2306 msg = "Test complex searchsorted with nans, side='r'"
2307 b = a.searchsorted(a, side='right')
2308 assert_equal(b, np.arange(1, 10), msg)
2309 msg = "Test searchsorted with little endian, side='l'"
2310 a = np.array([0, 128], dtype='<i4')
2311 b = a.searchsorted(np.array(128, dtype='<i4'))
2312 assert_equal(b, 1, msg)
2313 msg = "Test searchsorted with big endian, side='l'"
2314 a = np.array([0, 128], dtype='>i4')
2315 b = a.searchsorted(np.array(128, dtype='>i4'))
2316 assert_equal(b, 1, msg)
2317  
2318 # Check 0 elements
2319 a = np.ones(0)
2320 b = a.searchsorted([0, 1, 2], 'left')
2321 assert_equal(b, [0, 0, 0])
2322 b = a.searchsorted([0, 1, 2], 'right')
2323 assert_equal(b, [0, 0, 0])
2324 a = np.ones(1)
2325 # Check 1 element
2326 b = a.searchsorted([0, 1, 2], 'left')
2327 assert_equal(b, [0, 0, 1])
2328 b = a.searchsorted([0, 1, 2], 'right')
2329 assert_equal(b, [0, 1, 1])
2330 # Check all elements equal
2331 a = np.ones(2)
2332 b = a.searchsorted([0, 1, 2], 'left')
2333 assert_equal(b, [0, 0, 2])
2334 b = a.searchsorted([0, 1, 2], 'right')
2335 assert_equal(b, [0, 2, 2])
2336  
2337 # Test searching unaligned array
2338 a = np.arange(10)
2339 aligned = np.empty(a.itemsize * a.size + 1, 'uint8')
2340 unaligned = aligned[1:].view(a.dtype)
2341 unaligned[:] = a
2342 # Test searching unaligned array
2343 b = unaligned.searchsorted(a, 'left')
2344 assert_equal(b, a)
2345 b = unaligned.searchsorted(a, 'right')
2346 assert_equal(b, a + 1)
2347 # Test searching for unaligned keys
2348 b = a.searchsorted(unaligned, 'left')
2349 assert_equal(b, a)
2350 b = a.searchsorted(unaligned, 'right')
2351 assert_equal(b, a + 1)
2352  
2353 # Test smart resetting of binsearch indices
2354 a = np.arange(5)
2355 b = a.searchsorted([6, 5, 4], 'left')
2356 assert_equal(b, [5, 5, 4])
2357 b = a.searchsorted([6, 5, 4], 'right')
2358 assert_equal(b, [5, 5, 5])
2359  
2360 # Test all type specific binary search functions
2361 types = ''.join((np.typecodes['AllInteger'], np.typecodes['AllFloat'],
2362 np.typecodes['Datetime'], '?O'))
2363 for dt in types:
2364 if dt == 'M':
2365 dt = 'M8[D]'
2366 if dt == '?':
2367 a = np.arange(2, dtype=dt)
2368 out = np.arange(2)
2369 else:
2370 a = np.arange(0, 5, dtype=dt)
2371 out = np.arange(5)
2372 b = a.searchsorted(a, 'left')
2373 assert_equal(b, out)
2374 b = a.searchsorted(a, 'right')
2375 assert_equal(b, out + 1)
2376 # Test empty array, use a fresh array to get warnings in
2377 # valgrind if access happens.
2378 e = np.ndarray(shape=0, buffer=b'', dtype=dt)
2379 b = e.searchsorted(a, 'left')
2380 assert_array_equal(b, np.zeros(len(a), dtype=np.intp))
2381 b = a.searchsorted(e, 'left')
2382 assert_array_equal(b, np.zeros(0, dtype=np.intp))

2411 def test_searchsorted_with_invalid_sorter(self):
2412 a = np.array([5, 2, 1, 3, 4])
  • F841 Local variable 's' is assigned to but never used
2413 s = np.argsort(a)
2414 assert_raises(TypeError, np.searchsorted, a, 0,
2415 sorter=np.array((1, (2, 3)), dtype=object))
2416 assert_raises(TypeError, np.searchsorted, a, 0, sorter=[1.1])
2417 assert_raises(ValueError, np.searchsorted, a, 0, sorter=[1, 2, 3, 4])
  • E501 Line too long (83 > 79 characters)
2418 assert_raises(ValueError, np.searchsorted, a, 0, sorter=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6])
2419  
2420 # bounds check
  • E501 Line too long (80 > 79 characters)
2421 assert_raises(ValueError, np.searchsorted, a, 4, sorter=[0, 1, 2, 3, 5])
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
2422 assert_raises(ValueError, np.searchsorted, a, 0, sorter=[-1, 0, 1, 2, 3])
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
2423 assert_raises(ValueError, np.searchsorted, a, 0, sorter=[4, 0, -1, 2, 3])

2425 def test_searchsorted_with_sorter(self):
2426 a = np.random.rand(300)
2427 s = a.argsort()
2428 b = np.sort(a)
2429 k = np.linspace(0, 1, 20)
2430 assert_equal(b.searchsorted(k), a.searchsorted(k, sorter=s))
2431  
2432 a = np.array([0, 1, 2, 3, 5]*20)
2433 s = a.argsort()
2434 k = [0, 1, 2, 3, 5]
2435 expected = [0, 20, 40, 60, 80]
2436 assert_equal(a.searchsorted(k, side='left', sorter=s), expected)
2437 expected = [20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
2438 assert_equal(a.searchsorted(k, side='right', sorter=s), expected)
2439  
2440 # Test searching unaligned array
2441 keys = np.arange(10)
2442 a = keys.copy()
2443 np.random.shuffle(s)
2444 s = a.argsort()
2445 aligned = np.empty(a.itemsize * a.size + 1, 'uint8')
2446 unaligned = aligned[1:].view(a.dtype)
2447 # Test searching unaligned array
2448 unaligned[:] = a
2449 b = unaligned.searchsorted(keys, 'left', s)
2450 assert_equal(b, keys)
2451 b = unaligned.searchsorted(keys, 'right', s)
2452 assert_equal(b, keys + 1)
2453 # Test searching for unaligned keys
2454 unaligned[:] = keys
2455 b = a.searchsorted(unaligned, 'left', s)
2456 assert_equal(b, keys)
2457 b = a.searchsorted(unaligned, 'right', s)
2458 assert_equal(b, keys + 1)
2459  
2460 # Test all type specific indirect binary search functions
2461 types = ''.join((np.typecodes['AllInteger'], np.typecodes['AllFloat'],
2462 np.typecodes['Datetime'], '?O'))
2463 for dt in types:
2464 if dt == 'M':
2465 dt = 'M8[D]'
2466 if dt == '?':
2467 a = np.array([1, 0], dtype=dt)
2468 # We want the sorter array to be of a type that is different
2469 # from np.intp in all platforms, to check for #4698
2470 s = np.array([1, 0], dtype=np.int16)
2471 out = np.array([1, 0])
2472 else:
2473 a = np.array([3, 4, 1, 2, 0], dtype=dt)
2474 # We want the sorter array to be of a type that is different
2475 # from np.intp in all platforms, to check for #4698
2476 s = np.array([4, 2, 3, 0, 1], dtype=np.int16)
2477 out = np.array([3, 4, 1, 2, 0], dtype=np.intp)
2478 b = a.searchsorted(a, 'left', s)
2479 assert_equal(b, out)
2480 b = a.searchsorted(a, 'right', s)
2481 assert_equal(b, out + 1)
2482 # Test empty array, use a fresh array to get warnings in
2483 # valgrind if access happens.
2484 e = np.ndarray(shape=0, buffer=b'', dtype=dt)
2485 b = e.searchsorted(a, 'left', s[:0])
2486 assert_array_equal(b, np.zeros(len(a), dtype=np.intp))
2487 b = a.searchsorted(e, 'left', s)
2488 assert_array_equal(b, np.zeros(0, dtype=np.intp))
2489  
2490 # Test non-contiguous sorter array
2491 a = np.array([3, 4, 1, 2, 0])
2492 srt = np.empty((10,), dtype=np.intp)
2493 srt[1::2] = -1
2494 srt[::2] = [4, 2, 3, 0, 1]
2495 s = srt[::2]
2496 out = np.array([3, 4, 1, 2, 0], dtype=np.intp)
2497 b = a.searchsorted(a, 'left', s)
2498 assert_equal(b, out)
2499 b = a.searchsorted(a, 'right', s)
2500 assert_equal(b, out + 1)

2502 def test_searchsorted_return_type(self):
2503 # Functions returning indices should always return base ndarrays
2504 class A(np.ndarray):
2505 pass
2506 a = np.arange(5).view(A)
2507 b = np.arange(1, 3).view(A)
2508 s = np.arange(5).view(A)
2509 assert_(not isinstance(a.searchsorted(b, 'left'), A))
2510 assert_(not isinstance(a.searchsorted(b, 'right'), A))
2511 assert_(not isinstance(a.searchsorted(b, 'left', s), A))
2512 assert_(not isinstance(a.searchsorted(b, 'right', s), A))

2572 def test_partition(self):
2573 d = np.arange(10)
2574 assert_raises(TypeError, np.partition, d, 2, kind=1)
2575 assert_raises(ValueError, np.partition, d, 2, kind="nonsense")
2576 assert_raises(ValueError, np.argpartition, d, 2, kind="nonsense")
2577 assert_raises(ValueError, d.partition, 2, axis=0, kind="nonsense")
2578 assert_raises(ValueError, d.argpartition, 2, axis=0, kind="nonsense")
2579 for k in ("introselect",):
2580 d = np.array([])
2581 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 0, kind=k), d)
2582 assert_array_equal(np.argpartition(d, 0, kind=k), d)
2583 d = np.ones(1)
2584 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 0, kind=k)[0], d)
2585 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 0, kind=k)],
2586 np.partition(d, 0, kind=k))
2587  
2588 # kth not modified
2589 kth = np.array([30, 15, 5])
2590 okth = kth.copy()
2591 np.partition(np.arange(40), kth)
2592 assert_array_equal(kth, okth)
2593  
2594 for r in ([2, 1], [1, 2], [1, 1]):
2595 d = np.array(r)
2596 tgt = np.sort(d)
2597 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 0, kind=k)[0], tgt[0])
2598 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 1, kind=k)[1], tgt[1])
2599 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 0, kind=k)],
2600 np.partition(d, 0, kind=k))
2601 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 1, kind=k)],
2602 np.partition(d, 1, kind=k))
2603 for i in range(d.size):
2604 d[i:].partition(0, kind=k)
2605 assert_array_equal(d, tgt)
2606  
2607 for r in ([3, 2, 1], [1, 2, 3], [2, 1, 3], [2, 3, 1],
2608 [1, 1, 1], [1, 2, 2], [2, 2, 1], [1, 2, 1]):
2609 d = np.array(r)
2610 tgt = np.sort(d)
2611 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 0, kind=k)[0], tgt[0])
2612 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 1, kind=k)[1], tgt[1])
2613 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 2, kind=k)[2], tgt[2])
2614 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 0, kind=k)],
2615 np.partition(d, 0, kind=k))
2616 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 1, kind=k)],
2617 np.partition(d, 1, kind=k))
2618 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 2, kind=k)],
2619 np.partition(d, 2, kind=k))
2620 for i in range(d.size):
2621 d[i:].partition(0, kind=k)
2622 assert_array_equal(d, tgt)
2623  
2624 d = np.ones(50)
2625 assert_array_equal(np.partition(d, 0, kind=k), d)
2626 assert_array_equal(d[np.argpartition(d, 0, kind=k)],
2627 np.partition(d, 0, kind=k))
2628  
2629 # sorted

2786 prev = k + 1

3348 def test_swapaxes(self):
3349 a = np.arange(1*2*3*4).reshape(1, 2, 3, 4).copy()
3350 idx = np.indices(a.shape)
3351 assert_(a.flags['OWNDATA'])
3352 b = a.copy()
3353 # check exceptions
3354 assert_raises(np.AxisError, a.swapaxes, -5, 0)
3355 assert_raises(np.AxisError, a.swapaxes, 4, 0)
3356 assert_raises(np.AxisError, a.swapaxes, 0, -5)
3357 assert_raises(np.AxisError, a.swapaxes, 0, 4)
3358  
3359 for i in range(-4, 4):
3360 for j in range(-4, 4):
3361 for k, src in enumerate((a, b)):
3362 c = src.swapaxes(i, j)
3363 # check shape
3364 shape = list(src.shape)
3365 shape[i] = src.shape[j]
3366 shape[j] = src.shape[i]
3367 assert_equal(c.shape, shape, str((i, j, k)))
3368 # check array contents
3369 i0, i1, i2, i3 = [dim-1 for dim in c.shape]
3370 j0, j1, j2, j3 = [dim-1 for dim in src.shape]
3371 assert_equal(src[idx[j0], idx[j1], idx[j2], idx[j3]],
3372 c[idx[i0], idx[i1], idx[i2], idx[i3]],
3373 str((i, j, k)))
3374 # check a view is always returned, gh-5260
3375 assert_(not c.flags['OWNDATA'], str((i, j, k)))
3376 # check on non-contiguous input array
3377 if k == 1:
3378 b = c

3503 # ndarray.__rop__ always calls ufunc
3504 # ndarray.__iop__ always calls ufunc
3505 # ndarray.__op__, __rop__:
3506 # - defer if other has __array_ufunc__ and it is None
3507 # or other is not a subclass and has higher array priority
3508 # - else, call ufunc
3509 def test_ufunc_binop_interaction(self):
3510 # Python method name (without underscores)
3511 # -> (numpy ufunc, has_in_place_version, preferred_dtype)
3512 ops = {
3513 'add': (np.add, True, float),
3514 'sub': (np.subtract, True, float),
3515 'mul': (np.multiply, True, float),
3516 'truediv': (np.true_divide, True, float),
3517 'floordiv': (np.floor_divide, True, float),
3518 'mod': (np.remainder, True, float),
3519 'divmod': (np.divmod, False, float),
3520 'pow': (np.power, True, int),
3521 'lshift': (np.left_shift, True, int),
3522 'rshift': (np.right_shift, True, int),
3523 'and': (np.bitwise_and, True, int),
3524 'xor': (np.bitwise_xor, True, int),
3525 'or': (np.bitwise_or, True, int),
3526 'matmul': (np.matmul, False, float),
3527 # 'ge': (np.less_equal, False),
3528 # 'gt': (np.less, False),
3529 # 'le': (np.greater_equal, False),
3530 # 'lt': (np.greater, False),
3531 # 'eq': (np.equal, False),
3532 # 'ne': (np.not_equal, False),

3535 class Coerced(Exception):
3536 pass
3537  
3538 def array_impl(self):
3539 raise Coerced
3540  
3541 def op_impl(self, other):
3542 return "forward"
3543  
3544 def rop_impl(self, other):
3545 return "reverse"
3546  
3547 def iop_impl(self, other):
3548 return "in-place"
3549  
3550 def array_ufunc_impl(self, ufunc, method, *args, **kwargs):
3551 return ("__array_ufunc__", ufunc, method, args, kwargs)
3552  
3553 # Create an object with the given base, in the given module, with a
3554 # bunch of placeholder __op__ methods, and optionally a
3555 # __array_ufunc__ and __array_priority__.
3556 def make_obj(base, array_priority=False, array_ufunc=False,
3557 alleged_module="__main__"):
3558 class_namespace = {"__array__": array_impl}
3559 if array_priority is not False:
3560 class_namespace["__array_priority__"] = array_priority
3561 for op in ops:
3562 class_namespace["__{0}__".format(op)] = op_impl
3563 class_namespace["__r{0}__".format(op)] = rop_impl
3564 class_namespace["__i{0}__".format(op)] = iop_impl
3565 if array_ufunc is not False:
3566 class_namespace["__array_ufunc__"] = array_ufunc
3567 eval_namespace = {"base": base,
3568 "class_namespace": class_namespace,
3569 "__name__": alleged_module,
3570 }
3571 MyType = eval("type('MyType', (base,), class_namespace)",
3572 eval_namespace)
3573 if issubclass(MyType, np.ndarray):
3574 # Use this range to avoid special case weirdnesses around
3575 # divide-by-0, pow(x, 2), overflow due to pow(big, big), etc.
3576 return np.arange(3, 7).reshape(2, 2).view(MyType)
3577 else:
3578 return MyType()
3579  
3580 def check(obj, binop_override_expected, ufunc_override_expected,
3581 inplace_override_expected, check_scalar=True):
3582 for op, (ufunc, has_inplace, dtype) in ops.items():
3583 err_msg = ('op: %s, ufunc: %s, has_inplace: %s, dtype: %s'
3584 % (op, ufunc, has_inplace, dtype))
3585 check_objs = [np.arange(3, 7, dtype=dtype).reshape(2, 2)]
3586 if check_scalar:
3587 check_objs.append(check_objs[0][0])
3588 for arr in check_objs:
3589 arr_method = getattr(arr, "__{0}__".format(op))
3590  
3591 def first_out_arg(result):
3592 if op == "divmod":
3593 assert_(isinstance(result, tuple))
3594 return result[0]
3595 else:
3596 return result
3597  
3598 # arr __op__ obj
3599 if binop_override_expected:
3600 assert_equal(arr_method(obj), NotImplemented, err_msg)
3601 elif ufunc_override_expected:
3602 assert_equal(arr_method(obj)[0], "__array_ufunc__",
3603 err_msg)
3604 else:
3605 if (isinstance(obj, np.ndarray) and
3606 (type(obj).__array_ufunc__ is
3607 np.ndarray.__array_ufunc__)):
3608 # __array__ gets ignored
3609 res = first_out_arg(arr_method(obj))
3610 assert_(res.__class__ is obj.__class__, err_msg)
3611 else:
3612 assert_raises((TypeError, Coerced),
3613 arr_method, obj, err_msg=err_msg)
3614 # obj __op__ arr
3615 arr_rmethod = getattr(arr, "__r{0}__".format(op))
3616 if ufunc_override_expected:
3617 res = arr_rmethod(obj)
3618 assert_equal(res[0], "__array_ufunc__",
3619 err_msg=err_msg)
3620 assert_equal(res[1], ufunc, err_msg=err_msg)
3621 else:
3622 if (isinstance(obj, np.ndarray) and
3623 (type(obj).__array_ufunc__ is
3624 np.ndarray.__array_ufunc__)):
3625 # __array__ gets ignored
3626 res = first_out_arg(arr_rmethod(obj))
3627 assert_(res.__class__ is obj.__class__, err_msg)
3628 else:
3629 # __array_ufunc__ = "asdf" creates a TypeError
3630 assert_raises((TypeError, Coerced),
3631 arr_rmethod, obj, err_msg=err_msg)
3632  
3633 # arr __iop__ obj
3634 # array scalars don't have in-place operators
3635 if has_inplace and isinstance(arr, np.ndarray):
3636 arr_imethod = getattr(arr, "__i{0}__".format(op))
3637 if inplace_override_expected:
3638 assert_equal(arr_method(obj), NotImplemented,
3639 err_msg=err_msg)

3643 assert_equal(res[1], ufunc, err_msg)
3644 assert_(type(res[-1]["out"]) is tuple, err_msg)
3645 assert_(res[-1]["out"][0] is arr, err_msg)
3646 else:

3648 (type(obj).__array_ufunc__ is
  • E128 Continuation line under-indented for visual indent
3649 np.ndarray.__array_ufunc__)):
3650 # __array__ gets ignored
3651 assert_(arr_imethod(obj) is arr, err_msg)
3652 else:
3653 assert_raises((TypeError, Coerced),
3654 arr_imethod, obj,
3655 err_msg=err_msg)

3657 op_fn = getattr(operator, op, None)
3658 if op_fn is None:
3659 op_fn = getattr(operator, op + "_", None)
3660 if op_fn is None:
3661 op_fn = getattr(builtins, op)
3662 assert_equal(op_fn(obj, arr), "forward", err_msg)
3663 if not isinstance(obj, np.ndarray):
3664 if binop_override_expected:
3665 assert_equal(op_fn(arr, obj), "reverse", err_msg)
3666 elif ufunc_override_expected:

3671 err_msg)

3673 # No array priority, no array_ufunc -> nothing called
3674 check(make_obj(object), False, False, False)
3675 # Negative array priority, no array_ufunc -> nothing called
3676 # (has to be very negative, because scalar priority is -1000000.0)
3677 check(make_obj(object, array_priority=-2**30), False, False, False)
3678 # Positive array priority, no array_ufunc -> binops and iops only
3679 check(make_obj(object, array_priority=1), True, False, True)
3680 # ndarray ignores array_priority for ndarray subclasses
3681 check(make_obj(np.ndarray, array_priority=1), False, False, False,
3682 check_scalar=False)
3683 # Positive array_priority and array_ufunc -> array_ufunc only
3684 check(make_obj(object, array_priority=1,
3685 array_ufunc=array_ufunc_impl), False, True, False)
3686 check(make_obj(np.ndarray, array_priority=1,
3687 array_ufunc=array_ufunc_impl), False, True, False)
3688 # array_ufunc set to None -> defer binops only
3689 check(make_obj(object, array_ufunc=None), True, False, False)
3690 check(make_obj(np.ndarray, array_ufunc=None), True, False, False,
3691 check_scalar=False)

3709 def test_array_ufunc_index(self):
3710 # Check that index is set appropriately, also if only an output
3711 # is passed on (latter is another regression tests for github bug 4753)
3712 # This also checks implicitly that 'out' is always a tuple.
3713 class CheckIndex:
3714 def __array_ufunc__(self, ufunc, method, *inputs, **kw):
3715 for i, a in enumerate(inputs):
3716 if a is self:
3717 return i
3718 # calls below mean we must be in an output.
3719 for j, a in enumerate(kw['out']):
3720 if a is self:
3721 return (j,)
3722  
3723 a = CheckIndex()
3724 dummy = np.arange(2.)
3725 # 1 input, 1 output
3726 assert_equal(np.sin(a), 0)
3727 assert_equal(np.sin(dummy, a), (0,))
3728 assert_equal(np.sin(dummy, out=a), (0,))
3729 assert_equal(np.sin(dummy, out=(a,)), (0,))
3730 assert_equal(np.sin(a, a), 0)
3731 assert_equal(np.sin(a, out=a), 0)
3732 assert_equal(np.sin(a, out=(a,)), 0)
3733 # 1 input, 2 outputs
3734 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, a), (0,))
3735 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, None, a), (1,))
3736 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, dummy, a), (1,))
3737 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, out=(a, None)), (0,))
3738 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, out=(a, dummy)), (0,))
3739 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, out=(None, a)), (1,))
3740 assert_equal(np.modf(dummy, out=(dummy, a)), (1,))
3741 assert_equal(np.modf(a, out=(dummy, a)), 0)
3742 with assert_raises(TypeError):
3743 # Out argument must be tuple, since there are multiple outputs
3744 np.modf(dummy, out=a)
3745  
3746 assert_raises(ValueError, np.modf, dummy, out=(a,))
3747  
3748 # 2 inputs, 1 output
3749 assert_equal(np.add(a, dummy), 0)
3750 assert_equal(np.add(dummy, a), 1)
3751 assert_equal(np.add(dummy, dummy, a), (0,))
3752 assert_equal(np.add(dummy, a, a), 1)
3753 assert_equal(np.add(dummy, dummy, out=a), (0,))
3754 assert_equal(np.add(dummy, dummy, out=(a,)), (0,))
3755 assert_equal(np.add(a, dummy, out=a), 0)
3756  
3757 def test_out_override(self):
3758 # regression test for github bug 4753
3759 class OutClass(np.ndarray):
3760 def __array_ufunc__(self, ufunc, method, *inputs, **kw):
3761 if 'out' in kw:
3762 tmp_kw = kw.copy()
3763 tmp_kw.pop('out')
3764 func = getattr(ufunc, method)
3765 kw['out'][0][...] = func(*inputs, **tmp_kw)
3766  
3767 A = np.array([0]).view(OutClass)
3768 B = np.array([5])
3769 C = np.array([6])
3770 np.multiply(C, B, A)
3771 assert_equal(A[0], 30)
3772 assert_(isinstance(A, OutClass))
3773 A[0] = 0
3774 np.multiply(C, B, out=A)
3775 assert_equal(A[0], 30)
3776 assert_(isinstance(A, OutClass))

3799 def test_pow_array_object_dtype(self):
3800 # test pow on arrays of object dtype
3801 class SomeClass:
3802 def __init__(self, num=None):
3803 self.num = num
3804  
3805 # want to ensure a fast pow path is not taken
3806 def __mul__(self, other):
3807 raise AssertionError('__mul__ should not be called')
3808  
3809 def __div__(self, other):
3810 raise AssertionError('__div__ should not be called')
3811  
3812 def __pow__(self, exp):
3813 return SomeClass(num=self.num ** exp)
3814  
3815 def __eq__(self, other):
3816 if isinstance(other, SomeClass):
3817 return self.num == other.num
3818  
3819 __rpow__ = __pow__
3820  
3821 def pow_for(exp, arr):
3822 return np.array([x ** exp for x in arr])
3823  
3824 obj_arr = np.array([SomeClass(1), SomeClass(2), SomeClass(3)])
3825  
3826 assert_equal(obj_arr ** 0.5, pow_for(0.5, obj_arr))
3827 assert_equal(obj_arr ** 0, pow_for(0, obj_arr))
3828 assert_equal(obj_arr ** 1, pow_for(1, obj_arr))
3829 assert_equal(obj_arr ** -1, pow_for(-1, obj_arr))
3830 assert_equal(obj_arr ** 2, pow_for(2, obj_arr))

4027 def test_roundtrip(self):
4028 for proto in range(2, pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL + 1):
4029 carray = np.array([[2, 9], [7, 0], [3, 8]])
4030 DATA = [
4031 carray,
4032 np.transpose(carray),
4033 np.array([('xxx', 1, 2.0)], dtype=[('a', (str, 3)), ('b', int),
4034 ('c', float)])
4035 ]
4036  
4037 refs = [weakref.ref(a) for a in DATA]
4038 for a in DATA:
4039 assert_equal(
4040 a, pickle.loads(pickle.dumps(a, protocol=proto)),
4041 err_msg="%r" % a)
4042 del a, DATA, carray
4043 break_cycles()
4044 # check for reference leaks (gh-12793)
4045 for ref in refs:
4046 assert ref() is None

4578 class TestClip:
4579 def _check_range(self, x, cmin, cmax):
4580 assert_(np.all(x >= cmin))
4581 assert_(np.all(x <= cmax))
4582  
4583 def _clip_type(self, type_group, array_max,
4584 clip_min, clip_max, inplace=False,
4585 expected_min=None, expected_max=None):
4586 if expected_min is None:
4587 expected_min = clip_min
4588 if expected_max is None:
4589 expected_max = clip_max
4590  
4591 for T in np.sctypes[type_group]:
4592 if sys.byteorder == 'little':
4593 byte_orders = ['=', '>']
4594 else:
4595 byte_orders = ['<', '=']
4596  
4597 for byteorder in byte_orders:
4598 dtype = np.dtype(T).newbyteorder(byteorder)
4599  
4600 x = (np.random.random(1000) * array_max).astype(dtype)
4601 if inplace:
4602 # The tests that call us pass clip_min and clip_max that
4603 # might not fit in the destination dtype. They were written
4604 # assuming the previous unsafe casting, which now must be
4605 # passed explicitly to avoid a warning.
4606 x.clip(clip_min, clip_max, x, casting='unsafe')
4607 else:
4608 x = x.clip(clip_min, clip_max)
4609 byteorder = '='
4610  
4611 if x.dtype.byteorder == '|':
4612 byteorder = '|'
4613 assert_equal(x.dtype.byteorder, byteorder)
4614 self._check_range(x, expected_min, expected_max)
4615 return x
4616  
4617 def test_basic(self):
4618 for inplace in [False, True]:
4619 self._clip_type(
4620 'float', 1024, -12.8, 100.2, inplace=inplace)
4621 self._clip_type(
4622 'float', 1024, 0, 0, inplace=inplace)
4623  
4624 self._clip_type(
4625 'int', 1024, -120, 100, inplace=inplace)
4626 self._clip_type(
4627 'int', 1024, 0, 0, inplace=inplace)
4628  
4629 self._clip_type(
4630 'uint', 1024, 0, 0, inplace=inplace)
4631 self._clip_type(
4632 'uint', 1024, -120, 100, inplace=inplace, expected_min=0)
4633

5032 def test_file_position_after_tofile(self, tmp_filename):
5033 # gh-4118
5034 sizes = [io.DEFAULT_BUFFER_SIZE//8,
5035 io.DEFAULT_BUFFER_SIZE,
5036 io.DEFAULT_BUFFER_SIZE*8]
5037  
5038 for size in sizes:
5039 err_msg = "%d" % (size,)
5040  
5041 with open(tmp_filename, 'wb') as f:
5042 f.seek(size-1)
5043 f.write(b'\0')
5044 f.seek(10)
5045 f.write(b'12')
5046 np.array([0], dtype=np.float64).tofile(f)
5047 pos = f.tell()
5048 assert_equal(pos, 10 + 2 + 8, err_msg=err_msg)
5049  
5050 with open(tmp_filename, 'r+b') as f:
5051 f.read(2)
5052 f.seek(0, 1) # seek between read&write required by ANSI C
5053 np.array([0], dtype=np.float64).tofile(f)
5054 pos = f.tell()
5055 assert_equal(pos, 10, err_msg=err_msg)

5070 def test_fromfile_offset(self, x, tmp_filename):
5071 with open(tmp_filename, 'wb') as f:
5072 x.tofile(f)
5073  
5074 with open(tmp_filename, 'rb') as f:
5075 y = np.fromfile(f, dtype=x.dtype, offset=0)
5076 assert_array_equal(y, x.flat)
5077  
5078 with open(tmp_filename, 'rb') as f:
5079 count_items = len(x.flat) // 8
5080 offset_items = len(x.flat) // 4
5081 offset_bytes = x.dtype.itemsize * offset_items
5082 y = np.fromfile(
5083 f, dtype=x.dtype, count=count_items, offset=offset_bytes
5084 )
5085 assert_array_equal(
5086 y, x.flat[offset_items:offset_items+count_items]
5087 )
5088  
5089 # subsequent seeks should stack
5090 offset_bytes = x.dtype.itemsize
5091 z = np.fromfile(f, dtype=x.dtype, offset=offset_bytes)
5092 assert_array_equal(z, x.flat[offset_items+count_items+1:])
5093  
5094 with open(tmp_filename, 'wb') as f:
5095 x.tofile(f, sep=",")
5096

5099 TypeError,
5100 "'offset' argument only permitted for binary files",

5104 @pytest.mark.skipif(IS_PYPY, reason="bug in PyPy's PyNumber_AsSsize_t")
5105 def test_fromfile_bad_dup(self, x, tmp_filename):
5106 def dup_str(fd):
5107 return 'abc'
5108  
5109 def dup_bigint(fd):
5110 return 2**68
5111  
5112 old_dup = os.dup
5113 try:
5114 with open(tmp_filename, 'wb') as f:
5115 x.tofile(f)
5116 for dup, exc in ((dup_str, TypeError), (dup_bigint, OSError)):
5117 os.dup = dup
5118 assert_raises(exc, np.fromfile, f)
5119 finally:
5120 os.dup = old_dup

5122 def _check_from(self, s, value, filename, **kw):
5123 if 'sep' not in kw:
5124 y = np.frombuffer(s, **kw)
5125 else:
5126 y = np.fromstring(s, **kw)
5127 assert_array_equal(y, value)
5128  
5129 with open(filename, 'wb') as f:
5130 f.write(s)
5131 y = np.fromfile(filename, **kw)
5132 assert_array_equal(y, value)

5134 @pytest.fixture(params=["period", "comma"])
5135 def decimal_sep_localization(self, request):
5136 """
5137 Including this fixture in a test will automatically
5138 execute it with both types of decimal separator.
5139  
5140 So::
5141  
5142 def test_decimal(decimal_sep_localization):
5143 pass
5144  
5145 is equivalent to the following two tests::
5146  
5147 def test_decimal_period_separator():
5148 pass
5149  
5150 def test_decimal_comma_separator():
5151 with CommaDecimalPointLocale():
5152 pass
5153 """
5154 if request.param == "period":
5155 yield
5156 elif request.param == "comma":
5157 with CommaDecimalPointLocale():
5158 yield
5159 else:
5160 assert False, request.param
5161

5190 @pytest.mark.slow # takes > 1 minute on mechanical hard drive
5191 def test_big_binary(self):
5192 """Test workarounds for 32-bit limited fwrite, fseek, and ftell
5193 calls in windows. These normally would hang doing something like this.
5194 See http://projects.scipy.org/numpy/ticket/1660"""
5195 if sys.platform != 'win32':
5196 return
5197 try:
5198 # before workarounds, only up to 2**32-1 worked
5199 fourgbplus = 2**32 + 2**16
5200 testbytes = np.arange(8, dtype=np.int8)
5201 n = len(testbytes)
5202 flike = tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile()
5203 f = flike.file
5204 np.tile(testbytes, fourgbplus // testbytes.nbytes).tofile(f)
5205 flike.seek(0)
5206 a = np.fromfile(f, dtype=np.int8)
5207 flike.close()
5208 assert_(len(a) == fourgbplus)
5209 # check only start and end for speed:
5210 assert_((a[:n] == testbytes).all())
5211 assert_((a[-n:] == testbytes).all())
5212 except (MemoryError, ValueError):
5213 pass

5579 def test_field_names(self):
5580 # Test unicode and 8-bit / byte strings can be used
5581 a = np.zeros((1,), dtype=[('f1', 'i4'),
5582 ('f2', 'i4'),
5583 ('f3', [('sf1', 'i4')])])
5584 # byte string indexing fails gracefully
5585 assert_raises(IndexError, a.__setitem__, b'f1', 1)
5586 assert_raises(IndexError, a.__getitem__, b'f1')
5587 assert_raises(IndexError, a['f1'].__setitem__, b'sf1', 1)
5588 assert_raises(IndexError, a['f1'].__getitem__, b'sf1')
5589 b = a.copy()
5590 fn1 = str('f1')
5591 b[fn1] = 1
5592 assert_equal(b[fn1], 1)
5593 fnn = str('not at all')
5594 assert_raises(ValueError, b.__setitem__, fnn, 1)
5595 assert_raises(ValueError, b.__getitem__, fnn)
5596 b[0][fn1] = 2
5597 assert_equal(b[fn1], 2)
5598 # Subfield
5599 assert_raises(ValueError, b[0].__setitem__, fnn, 1)
5600 assert_raises(ValueError, b[0].__getitem__, fnn)
5601 # Subfield
5602 fn3 = str('f3')
5603 sfn1 = str('sf1')
5604 b[fn3][sfn1] = 1
5605 assert_equal(b[fn3][sfn1], 1)

5797 for ddof in range(3):

5800 res = f(self.rmat, axis=1, ddof=ddof) * (dim - ddof)

5803 dim = self.rmat.shape[1]

5805 res = f(self.rmat, axis=1, ddof=ddof) * np.sqrt(dim - ddof)
5806 assert_almost_equal(res, tgt)
5807 assert_almost_equal(res, tgt)

5892 def test_var_values(self):
5893 for mat in [self.rmat, self.cmat, self.omat]:
5894 for axis in [0, 1, None]:
5895 msqr = _mean(mat * mat.conj(), axis=axis)
5896 mean = _mean(mat, axis=axis)
5897 tgt = msqr - mean * mean.conjugate()
5898 res = _var(mat, axis=axis)
5899 assert_almost_equal(res, tgt)
5900  
5901 @pytest.mark.parametrize(('complex_dtype', 'ndec'), (
5902 ('complex64', 6),
5903 ('complex128', 7),
5904 ('clongdouble', 7),
5905 ))
5906 def test_var_complex_values(self, complex_dtype, ndec):
5907 # Test fast-paths for every builtin complex type
5908 for axis in [0, 1, None]:
5909 mat = self.cmat.copy().astype(complex_dtype)
5910 msqr = _mean(mat * mat.conj(), axis=axis)
5911 mean = _mean(mat, axis=axis)
5912 tgt = msqr - mean * mean.conjugate()
5913 res = _var(mat, axis=axis)
5914 assert_almost_equal(res, tgt, decimal=ndec)

5921 msqr = _mean(mat * mat.conj(), axis=axis)
5922 mean = _mean(mat, axis=axis)
5923 tgt = msqr - mean * mean.conjugate()
5924 res = _var(mat, axis=axis)
5925 assert_almost_equal(res, tgt)

6028 def test_subclass(self):
6029 class TestArray(np.ndarray):
6030 def __new__(cls, data, info):
6031 result = np.array(data)
6032 result = result.view(cls)
6033 result.info = info
6034 return result
6035  
6036 def __array_finalize__(self, obj):
6037 self.info = getattr(obj, "info", '')
6038  
6039 dat = TestArray([[1, 2, 3, 4], [5, 6, 7, 8]], 'jubba')
6040 res = dat.mean(1)
6041 assert_(res.info == dat.info)
6042 res = dat.std(1)
6043 assert_(res.info == dat.info)
6044 res = dat.var(1)
6045 assert_(res.info == dat.info)

6048 class TestVdot:
6049 def test_basic(self):
6050 dt_numeric = np.typecodes['AllFloat'] + np.typecodes['AllInteger']
6051 dt_complex = np.typecodes['Complex']
6052  
6053 # test real
6054 a = np.eye(3)
6055 for dt in dt_numeric + 'O':
6056 b = a.astype(dt)
6057 res = np.vdot(b, b)
6058 assert_(np.isscalar(res))
6059 assert_equal(np.vdot(b, b), 3)
6060  
6061 # test complex
6062 a = np.eye(3) * 1j
6063 for dt in dt_complex + 'O':
6064 b = a.astype(dt)
6065 res = np.vdot(b, b)
6066 assert_(np.isscalar(res))
6067 assert_equal(np.vdot(b, b), 3)
6068  
6069 # test boolean
6070 b = np.eye(3, dtype=bool)
6071 res = np.vdot(b, b)
6072 assert_(np.isscalar(res))
6073 assert_equal(np.vdot(b, b), True)
6074  
6075 def test_vdot_array_order(self):
6076 a = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]], order='C')
6077 b = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]], order='F')
6078 res = np.vdot(a, a)
6079  
6080 # integer arrays are exact
6081 assert_equal(np.vdot(a, b), res)
6082 assert_equal(np.vdot(b, a), res)
6083 assert_equal(np.vdot(b, b), res)
6084  
6085 def test_vdot_uncontiguous(self):
6086 for size in [2, 1000]:
6087 # Different sizes match different branches in vdot.
6088 a = np.zeros((size, 2, 2))
6089 b = np.zeros((size, 2, 2))
6090 a[:, 0, 0] = np.arange(size)
6091 b[:, 0, 0] = np.arange(size) + 1
6092 # Make a and b uncontiguous:
6093 a = a[..., 0]
6094 b = b[..., 0]
6095  
6096 assert_equal(np.vdot(a, b),
6097 np.vdot(a.flatten(), b.flatten()))
6098 assert_equal(np.vdot(a, b.copy()),
6099 np.vdot(a.flatten(), b.flatten()))
6100 assert_equal(np.vdot(a.copy(), b),
6101 np.vdot(a.flatten(), b.flatten()))
6102 assert_equal(np.vdot(a.copy('F'), b),
6103 np.vdot(a.flatten(), b.flatten()))
6104 assert_equal(np.vdot(a, b.copy('F')),
6105 np.vdot(a.flatten(), b.flatten()))
6106

6209 def test_vecobject(self):
6210 class Vec:
6211 def __init__(self, sequence=None):
6212 if sequence is None:
6213 sequence = []
6214 self.array = np.array(sequence)
6215  
6216 def __add__(self, other):
6217 out = Vec()
6218 out.array = self.array + other.array
6219 return out
6220  
6221 def __sub__(self, other):
6222 out = Vec()
6223 out.array = self.array - other.array
6224 return out
6225  
6226 def __mul__(self, other): # with scalar
6227 out = Vec(self.array.copy())
6228 out.array *= other
6229 return out
6230  
6231 def __rmul__(self, other):
6232 return self*other
6233  
6234 U_non_cont = np.transpose([[1., 1.], [1., 2.]])
6235 U_cont = np.ascontiguousarray(U_non_cont)
6236 x = np.array([Vec([1., 0.]), Vec([0., 1.])])
6237 zeros = np.array([Vec([0., 0.]), Vec([0., 0.])])
6238 zeros_test = np.dot(U_cont, x) - np.dot(U_non_cont, x)
6239 assert_equal(zeros[0].array, zeros_test[0].array)
6240 assert_equal(zeros[1].array, zeros_test[1].array)

6314 def test_accelerate_framework_sgemv_fix(self):
6315  
6316 def aligned_array(shape, align, dtype, order='C'):
6317 d = dtype(0)
6318 N = np.prod(shape)
6319 tmp = np.zeros(N * d.nbytes + align, dtype=np.uint8)
6320 address = tmp.__array_interface__["data"][0]
6321 for offset in range(align):
6322 if (address + offset) % align == 0:
6323 break
6324 tmp = tmp[offset:offset+N*d.nbytes].view(dtype=dtype)
6325 return tmp.reshape(shape, order=order)
6326  
6327 def as_aligned(arr, align, dtype, order='C'):
6328 aligned = aligned_array(arr.shape, align, dtype, order)
6329 aligned[:] = arr[:]
6330 return aligned
6331  
6332 def assert_dot_close(A, X, desired):
6333 assert_allclose(np.dot(A, X), desired, rtol=1e-5, atol=1e-7)
6334  
6335 m = aligned_array(100, 15, np.float32)
6336 s = aligned_array((100, 100), 15, np.float32)
6337 np.dot(s, m) # this will always segfault if the bug is present
6338  
6339 testdata = itertools.product((15, 32), (10000,), (200, 89), ('C', 'F'))
6340 for align, m, n, a_order in testdata:
6341 # Calculation in double precision
6342 A_d = np.random.rand(m, n)
6343 X_d = np.random.rand(n)
6344 desired = np.dot(A_d, X_d)
6345 # Calculation with aligned single precision
6346 A_f = as_aligned(A_d, align, np.float32, order=a_order)
6347 X_f = as_aligned(X_d, align, np.float32)
6348 assert_dot_close(A_f, X_f, desired)
6349 # Strided A rows
6350 A_d_2 = A_d[::2]
6351 desired = np.dot(A_d_2, X_d)
6352 A_f_2 = A_f[::2]
6353 assert_dot_close(A_f_2, X_f, desired)
6354 # Strided A columns, strided X vector
6355 A_d_22 = A_d_2[:, ::2]
6356 X_d_2 = X_d[::2]
6357 desired = np.dot(A_d_22, X_d_2)
6358 A_f_22 = A_f_2[:, ::2]
6359 X_f_2 = X_f[::2]
6360 assert_dot_close(A_f_22, X_f_2, desired)
6361 # Check the strides are as expected
6362 if a_order == 'F':
6363 assert_equal(A_f_22.strides, (8, 8 * m))
6364 else:
6365 assert_equal(A_f_22.strides, (8 * n, 8))
6366 assert_equal(X_f_2.strides, (8,))
6367 # Strides in A rows + cols only
6368 X_f_2c = as_aligned(X_f_2, align, np.float32)
6369 assert_dot_close(A_f_22, X_f_2c, desired)
6370 # Strides just in A cols
6371 A_d_12 = A_d[:, ::2]
6372 desired = np.dot(A_d_12, X_d_2)
6373 A_f_12 = A_f[:, ::2]
6374 assert_dot_close(A_f_12, X_f_2c, desired)
6375 # Strides in A cols and X
6376 assert_dot_close(A_f_12, X_f_2, desired)

6641 def test_out_contiguous(self):

6643 b = np.array([[1, 3], [5, 7]], dtype=float)
6644 v = np.array([1, 3], dtype=float)
6645 tgt = np.dot(a, b)
6646 tgt_mv = np.dot(a, v)
6647  
6648 # test out non-contiguous
6649 out = np.ones((5, 2, 2), dtype=float)
6650 c = self.matmul(a, b, out=out[..., 0])
6651 assert c.base is out
6652 assert_array_equal(c, tgt)

6838 def test_inner_product_with_various_contiguities(self):
6839 # github issue 6532
6840 for dt in np.typecodes['AllInteger'] + np.typecodes['AllFloat'] + '?':
6841 # check an inner product involving a matrix transpose
6842 A = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]], dtype=dt)
6843 B = np.array([[1, 3], [2, 4]], dtype=dt)
6844 C = np.array([1, 1], dtype=dt)
6845 desired = np.array([4, 6], dtype=dt)
6846 assert_equal(np.inner(A.T, C), desired)
6847 assert_equal(np.inner(C, A.T), desired)
6848 assert_equal(np.inner(B, C), desired)
6849 assert_equal(np.inner(C, B), desired)
6850 # check a matrix product
6851 desired = np.array([[7, 10], [15, 22]], dtype=dt)
6852 assert_equal(np.inner(A, B), desired)
6853 # check the syrk vs. gemm paths
6854 desired = np.array([[5, 11], [11, 25]], dtype=dt)
6855 assert_equal(np.inner(A, A), desired)
6856 assert_equal(np.inner(A, A.copy()), desired)
6857 # check an inner product involving an aliased and reversed view
6858 a = np.arange(5).astype(dt)
6859 b = a[::-1]
6860 desired = np.array(10, dtype=dt).item()
6861 assert_equal(np.inner(b, a), desired)

7269 def test_native_padding(self):
7270 align = np.dtype('i').alignment
7271 for j in range(8):
7272 if j == 0:
7273 s = 'bi'
7274 else:
7275 s = 'b%dxi' % j
7276 self._check('@'+s, {'f0': ('i1', 0),
7277 'f1': ('i', align*(1 + j//align))})
7278 self._check('='+s, {'f0': ('i1', 0),
7279 'f1': ('i', 1+j)})
7280  
7281 def test_native_padding_2(self):
7282 # Native padding should work also for structs and sub-arrays
7283 self._check('x3T{xi}', {'f0': (({'f0': ('i', 4)}, (3,)), 4)})
7284 self._check('^x3T{xi}', {'f0': (({'f0': ('i', 1)}, (3,)), 1)})

7286 def test_trailing_padding(self):
7287 # Trailing padding should be included, *and*, the item size
7288 # should match the alignment if in aligned mode
7289 align = np.dtype('i').alignment
7290 size = np.dtype('i').itemsize
7291  
7292 def aligned(n):
7293 return align*(1 + (n-1)//align)
7294  
7295 base = dict(formats=['i'], names=['f0'])
7296  
7297 self._check('ix', dict(itemsize=aligned(size + 1), **base))
7298 self._check('ixx', dict(itemsize=aligned(size + 2), **base))
7299 self._check('ixxx', dict(itemsize=aligned(size + 3), **base))
7300 self._check('ixxxx', dict(itemsize=aligned(size + 4), **base))
7301 self._check('i7x', dict(itemsize=aligned(size + 7), **base))
7302  
7303 self._check('^ix', dict(itemsize=size + 1, **base))
7304 self._check('^ixx', dict(itemsize=size + 2, **base))
7305 self._check('^ixxx', dict(itemsize=size + 3, **base))
7306 self._check('^ixxxx', dict(itemsize=size + 4, **base))
7307 self._check('^i7x', dict(itemsize=size + 7, **base))

7847 def test_compatible_cast(self):
7848  
7849 # Some types are compatible even though they are different, no
7850 # copy is necessary for them. This is mostly true for some integers
7851 def int_types(byteswap=False):
7852 int_types = (np.typecodes["Integer"] +
7853 np.typecodes["UnsignedInteger"])
7854 for int_type in int_types:
7855 yield np.dtype(int_type)
7856 if byteswap:
7857 yield np.dtype(int_type).newbyteorder()
7858  
7859 for int1 in int_types():
7860 for int2 in int_types(True):
7861 arr = np.arange(10, dtype=int1)
7862  
7863 for copy in self.true_vals:
7864 res = np.array(arr, copy=copy, dtype=int2)
7865 assert res is not arr and res.flags.owndata
7866 assert_array_equal(res, arr)
7867  
7868 if int1 == int2:
7869 # Casting is not necessary, base check is sufficient here
7870 for copy in self.false_vals:
7871 res = np.array(arr, copy=copy, dtype=int2)
7872 assert res is arr or res.base is arr
7873  
7874 res = np.array(arr,
7875 copy=np._CopyMode.NEVER,
7876 dtype=int2)
7877 assert res is arr or res.base is arr
7878  
7879 else:
7880 # Casting is necessary, assert copy works:
7881 for copy in self.false_vals:
7882 res = np.array(arr, copy=copy, dtype=int2)
7883 assert res is not arr and res.flags.owndata
7884 assert_array_equal(res, arr)
7885  
7886 assert_raises(ValueError, np.array,
7887 arr, copy=np._CopyMode.NEVER,
7888 dtype=int2)
7889 assert_raises(ValueError, np.array,
7890 arr, copy=None,
7891 dtype=int2)

7952 @pytest.mark.parametrize(
7953 "arr", [np.ones(()), np.arange(81).reshape((9, 9))])
7954 @pytest.mark.parametrize("order1", ["C", "F", None])
7955 @pytest.mark.parametrize("order2", ["C", "F", "A", "K"])
7956 def test_order_mismatch(self, arr, order1, order2):
7957 # The order is the main (python side) reason that can cause
7958 # a never-copy to fail.
7959 # Prepare C-order, F-order and non-contiguous arrays:
7960 arr = arr.copy(order1)
7961 if order1 == "C":
7962 assert arr.flags.c_contiguous
7963 elif order1 == "F":
7964 assert arr.flags.f_contiguous
7965 elif arr.ndim != 0:
7966 # Make array non-contiguous
7967 arr = arr[::2, ::2]
7968 assert not arr.flags.forc
7969  
7970 # Whether a copy is necessary depends on the order of arr:
7971 if order2 == "C":
7972 no_copy_necessary = arr.flags.c_contiguous
7973 elif order2 == "F":
7974 no_copy_necessary = arr.flags.f_contiguous
7975 else:
7976 # Keeporder and Anyorder are OK with non-contiguous output.
7977 # This is not consistent with the `astype` behaviour which
7978 # enforces contiguity for "A". It is probably historic from when
7979 # "K" did not exist.
7980 no_copy_necessary = True
7981  
7982 # Test it for both the array and a memoryview
7983 for view in [arr, memoryview(arr)]:
7984 for copy in self.true_vals:
7985 res = np.array(view, copy=copy, order=order2)
7986 assert res is not arr and res.flags.owndata
7987 assert_array_equal(arr, res)
7988  
7989 if no_copy_necessary:
7990 for copy in self.false_vals:
7991 res = np.array(view, copy=copy, order=order2)
7992 # res.base.obj refers to the memoryview
7993 if not IS_PYPY:
7994 assert res is arr or res.base.obj is arr
7995  
7996 res = np.array(view, copy=np._CopyMode.NEVER,
7997 order=order2)
7998 if not IS_PYPY:
7999 assert res is arr or res.base.obj is arr
8000 else:
8001 for copy in self.false_vals:
8002 res = np.array(arr, copy=copy, order=order2)
8003 assert_array_equal(arr, res)
8004 assert_raises(ValueError, np.array,
8005 view, copy=np._CopyMode.NEVER,
8006 order=order2)
8007 assert_raises(ValueError, np.array,
8008 view, copy=None,
8009 order=order2)
8010

8243 # All integer

8250 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))
8251 assert_(not np.array(1, dtype=dt1) < np.array(0, dtype=dt2),
8252 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))
8253  
8254 # Unsigned integers
8255 for dt1 in 'BHILQP':
8256 assert_(-1 < np.array(1, dtype=dt1), "type %s failed" % (dt1,))
8257 assert_(not -1 > np.array(1, dtype=dt1), "type %s failed" % (dt1,))
8258 assert_(-1 != np.array(1, dtype=dt1), "type %s failed" % (dt1,))
8259  
8260 # Unsigned vs signed
8261 for dt2 in 'bhilqp':
8262 assert_(np.array(1, dtype=dt1) > np.array(-1, dtype=dt2),
8263 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))

8265 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))
8266 assert_(np.array(1, dtype=dt1) != np.array(-1, dtype=dt2),
8267 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))

8272 assert_(not 1 < np.array(-1, dtype=dt1), "type %s failed" % (dt1,))
8273 assert_(-1 == np.array(-1, dtype=dt1), "type %s failed" % (dt1,))
8274

8277 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))
8278 assert_(not np.array(1, dtype=dt1) < np.array(-1, dtype=dt2),
8279 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))
8280 assert_(np.array(-1, dtype=dt1) == np.array(-1, dtype=dt2),
8281 "type %s and %s failed" % (dt1, dt2))

9100 def test_uintalignment_and_alignment():

9106 # Complex types are the main problem, whose alignment may not be the same

9111 # for DEBUG=1.

9136 class TestAlignment:
9137 # adapted from scipy._lib.tests.test__util.test__aligned_zeros
9138 # Checks that unusual memory alignments don't trip up numpy.
9139 # In particular, check RELAXED_STRIDES don't trip alignment assertions in
9140 # NDEBUG mode for size-0 arrays (gh-12503)
9141  
9142 def check(self, shape, dtype, order, align):
9143 err_msg = repr((shape, dtype, order, align))
9144 x = _aligned_zeros(shape, dtype, order, align=align)
9145 if align is None:
9146 align = np.dtype(dtype).alignment
9147 assert_equal(x.__array_interface__['data'][0] % align, 0)
9148 if hasattr(shape, '__len__'):
9149 assert_equal(x.shape, shape, err_msg)
9150 else:
9151 assert_equal(x.shape, (shape,), err_msg)
9152 assert_equal(x.dtype, dtype)
9153 if order == "C":
9154 assert_(x.flags.c_contiguous, err_msg)
9155 elif order == "F":
9156 if x.size > 0:
9157 assert_(x.flags.f_contiguous, err_msg)
9158 elif order is None:
9159 assert_(x.flags.c_contiguous, err_msg)
9160 else:
9161 raise ValueError()
9162  
9163 def test_various_alignments(self):
9164 for align in [1, 2, 3, 4, 8, 12, 16, 32, 64, None]:
9165 for n in [0, 1, 3, 11]:
9166 for order in ["C", "F", None]:
9167 for dtype in list(np.typecodes["All"]) + ['i4,i4,i4']:
9168 if dtype == 'O':
9169 # object dtype can't be misaligned
9170 continue
9171 for shape in [n, (1, 2, 3, n)]:
9172 self.check(shape, np.dtype(dtype), order, align)
9173
